Governor Perdue,



I want to express my appreciation for your continued support in understanding the importance of Early Childhood Programs.  Recent research shows a direct correlation between quality Early Childhood Programs for students at risk and the drop out rate, the incarceration rate and the ability to financially maintain oneself rather that relying on welfare.  Students at risk can never catch up to their peers without a direct intervention before entering kindergarten because of the deceit in their language and early literacy skills.  These children enter kindergarten with a huge gap in their ability to learn to read. Without closing this  Achievement Gap we will continue to pay heavy tax dollars in incarcerating these young adults, paying for the children that they have through Medicare and WIC and also the countless other tax dollars that are spent because they are not capable of maintaining full-time work.



I have attached or copied the recent research that I have read so that you may be well aware of the importance of Early Childhood Programs.  Please continue to make this one of your top priorities so that at risk children can have the opportunity to enter kindergarten ready to learn, have successful school careers and graduate to become viable citizens of our communalities.





Rebecca Carter

Assistant Principal

Tryon Hills Pre-Kindergarten





